<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="187" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,968,2039]" pageId="2" pageNumber="187">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1976,2002]" pageId="2" pageNumber="187">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tong &amp; Zhang &amp; Chen &amp; Wang" authorityYear="2019" box="[567,653,1976,2002]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Shirozuella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="187" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="limbata">
<emphasis box="[567,653,1976,2002]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="187">limbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
derives from the Latin word limbus (=marginal). It refers to the external borders of the elytra, which are rather explanate-reflexed. It is a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
